Data Issues:¶

  • We don't need these columns in our analysis (start_station_latitude,start_station_longitude,end_station_latitude,end_station_longitude, start_station_id, end_station_id, bike_id,bike_share_for_all_trip).
  • There is missing values in (start_station_name, end_station_name)
  • (start_time, end_time, member_birth_year) not in appropriate dtypes.
  • We need to extract hour, day of week, and date from start_time and end_time columns and age from member_birth_year column.
  • We also need to conver the duration from second to minutes.

Issue 4¶

Define¶

We need to extract hour, day of week, and date from start_time and end_time columns and age from member_birth_year column also extract the duration in minutes. so, we'll use .dt function and we calculate the age by subtracting the current year from the year of birth.

Code¶

In [336]:
def new_column(col1,col2,col3,col):
    ''' This function is to extract hour, day of week, and date from specific column '''
    df.loc[:, col1] = df.loc[:, col].dt.hour
    df.loc[:, col2] = df.loc[:, col].dt.day_name()
    df.loc[:, col3] = df.loc[:, col].dt.date

    pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None  # default='warn'
    

#extract hour, day of week, and date from `start_time` and `end_time` columns
new_column('start_hour','day_of_week_start','start_date','start_time')
new_column('end_hour' ,'day_of_week_end' ,'end_date' ,'end_time')
In [337]:
#calculate the age by subtracting the current year from the year of birth
df.loc[:, 'age'] = 2021 - df.member_birth_year
In [338]:
#extract the duration in minutes 
df.loc[:, 'duration_min'] = df.loc[:, 'end_time'] - df.loc[:, 'start_time']
df.loc[:, 'duration_min']= df.loc[:, 'duration_min']/np.timedelta64(1,'m')

Now All Issues Are Fixed¶

There are 174,952 trips in this dataset. It happened in February and early March of 2019. The number of trips increases more on weekdays than on weekends (Saturday, sunday), and most trips on weekdays are on Thursdays with more than 30000 trips. Most trips times start and end from the 8 am to 9 am in the morning and from 4 pm to 6 pm in the evening, while the least times are between midnight and 5 am. The most popular time for the start and end of the trip is 5 pm with more than 20,000 trips and the lowest time is 3 am with less than 2,500 trips. Out of 174,952 trips, more than 140,000 were subscribers and less than 20,000 were customers. This means that the subscribers (approximately 91% of users) was higher than that of customers (approximately 9%). The number of male users was higher by more than 120,000 trips (almost 75%). The most two popular start and end stations is Market St at 10th St and San Francisco Caltrain Station 2 (Townsend St at 4th St). This distribution is skewed right and show that the median of trip duration is about 8 min. This distribution is skewed right and show that the median of users age is about 30 years. The boxplot show that the age range is between 20 - 60 years.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

- What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 174,952 bike trips in this dataset that happened in February and 1st, March of 2019. The dataset consists of 16 features ('duration_sec', 'start_time', 'end_time', 'start_station_name', 'end_station_name', 'user_type', 'member_birth_year', 'member_gender', 'start_hour', 'day_of_week_start', 'start_date', 'end_hour', 'day_of_week_end', 'end_date', 'age', 'duration_min'). Most variables are numeric, but 6 variables are categorical, which: start_station_name, end_station_name, user_type, member_gender, day_of_week_start and day_of_week_end.

(Station): There are 329 satation.

(Date): Happened in February and 1st, March of 2019

(user_type): There are two types of user Subscribers and Customer

- What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in 3 features: start_hour, day_of_week_start, and duration_min

- What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the user_type, member_gender, start_date, and age will help in our investigation.

    ''' This function is to create bar chart'''

    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data = df, y = col, color = base_color, order = count)

    plt.title(title);

def bar_pie(col, title1, title2):
    '''This function is to create both bar chart and pie chart side by side '''
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1) 
    order = df[col].value_counts().index
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data = df, x = col, color = base_color, order = order);
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90);
    plt.title(title1, size = 16);


    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2) 
    order = df[col].value_counts()
    plt.pie(order , labels = order.index , startangle = 90, counterclock = False, autopct='%1.2f%%');
    plt.title(title2, fontsize= 18);

def group_plot(col1, col2, title):
    '''This function is to group by columns and plot a heatmap and bar chart '''
    counts = df.groupby([col1, col2]).size()
    counts = counts.reset_index(name='count')
    counts = counts.pivot(index = col1, columns = col2, values = 'count')

def clustered_bar(col1,col2,title):
    '''This function is to create clustered bar chart'''
    counts = df.groupby([col1, col2]).size()
    counts = counts.reset_index(name='count')
    counts = counts.pivot(index = col1, columns = col2, values = 'count')
    
    counts.plot(kind='bar', figsize = (8,8))
    plt.title(title);

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [492]:
def heatmap_bar(cat_col1, cat_col2,num_col, title, title2):
    '''This function is to create heatmap and bar chart together for 3 different columns'''
    plt.figure(figsize = [20, 10])
    median = df.groupby([cat_col1, cat_col2]).median()[num_col]
    median = median.reset_index(name = num_col)
    median = median.pivot(index = cat_col1, columns = cat_col2,
                            values = num_col)
    sb.heatmap(median, annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
           cbar_kws = {'label' : title})
    plt.title(title2);
    
    plt.figure(figsize = [8, 8])
    ax = sb.barplot(data = df, x = cat_col2 , y = num_col  , hue = cat_col1)
    ax.legend(loc = 8, ncol = 3, framealpha = 1, title = cat_col2)
    plt.title(title2);

The median age for customer and subscriber users is almost similar in weekdays and weekend and the highest median age was for customer user on Wednesday (35 years).
